            <fr:addr type="user">algm-0022</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>algm-0022.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Dense subsite of affine opens">Dense subsite of affine opens</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>Given a <fr:link href="algm-000R.xml" title="Scheme" addr="algm-000R" type="local">scheme</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>, the underlying locale (equipped with the canonical coverage) has a <fr:link href="algm-0021.xml" title="Dense subsite" addr="algm-0021" type="local">dense subsite</fr:link> whose objects are affine opens, and morphisms are distinguished open subspaces. Note that this isn’t a full subcategory, since <fr:link href="algm-0020.xml" title="A non-distinguished affine subscheme" addr="algm-0020" type="local">there exist affine open subspaces that are not distinguished</fr:link>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Since schemes are covered by affine schemes, and distinguished opens form a basis in the <fr:link href="algm-0007.xml" title="Localic spectrum of a commutative ring" addr="algm-0007" type="local">localic spectrum of a commutative ring</fr:link>, every open in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is covered by affine opens. On the other hand, <fr:link href="algm-0016.xml" title="Nike’s trick" addr="algm-0016" type="local">Nike’s trick</fr:link> guarantees the condition on morphisms for dense subsites.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
